</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">People formerly suffered from hunger in the North, but this was generally owing to the inveteracy of separate Interests, the profligacy of the men and the ignorance of their leaders &#8211; for many years past, the trade being carried on with order and tranquillity, we hear few or no starving tales from any quarter.  It is true men who travel or live with Indians sometimes fast many days at intervals in the course of a winter &#8211; but this often happen more through want of foresight, industry, or management than any other cause.  I have been here these eleven years, always travelling in the worst posts in the Country for living: yet never went to bed without supper; nor have I the least knowledge of having ever eaten any thing unclean or prohibited in civilized countries.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The North is divided into Several Departments; in which ten years ago there were no more than eight or nine Posts &#8211; but now more than forty.  The Forts are situated in places the most eligible for the trade and furnished with every conveniency suitable to the Country and the purposes of the Company.</p>
